SIMPLE: prescriptive
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prescriptive
<hw>Pre*scrip"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praescriptivus</ets> of a demurrer or legal exception.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Consisting in, or acquired by,
immemorial or long-continued use and enjoyment; <as>as, a
<ex>prescriptive</ex> right of title</as>; pleading the continuance and
authority of long custom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The right to be drowsy in protracted toil has become
<qex>prescriptive</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. M. Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the doctrine that acceptable
grammatical rules should be prescribed by authority, rather than be
determined by common usage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>prescriptivism</ent>⟦br⟧
